\begin_layout Standard
The large scale eddies are highly isotropic.
 The mean flow is component is usually dominant to the fluctuations.
 The velocity fluctuations have three components and the component aligning
 to the mean flow is usually larger than the other two.
 If there is a wall nearby, the component normal to the wall becomes small.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The small scales, however, are dominated by local phenomena and are isotropic.
 The energy cascade was studied by Kolmogorov and it is widely accepted
 to have a certain, well known, shape.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many turbulence models are based on these two concepts: energy cascade and
 isotropic small scale turbulence.
 Using turbulence models, it is not necessary to model the small scale phenomena.
