\begin_layout Subsection
Model categories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Direct numerical simulation - DNS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Direct numerical simulation (DNS) is conceptually the most simple approach
 to turbulence modeling.
 It uses no additional models to the governing equations descried in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Fluid-flow"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to directly model all the scales of turbulence down to Kolmogorov
 microscales, a very fine mesh and very small time step are needed.
 This makes DNS extremely computationally expensive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DNS is mostly as a academical tool in turbulence modeling.
 A high quality DNS model gives near exact information about the flow.
 The detailed information helps researchers to develop better turbulence
 models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Large eddy simulation - LES
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Large eddy simulation (LES) is the intermediate step between direct simulation
 (DNS) and Reynolds averaging (RANS).
 As name states, the large eddies are solved directly, like in DNS, but
 the small eddies are modeled with additional simplifications.
 In order to solve the large eddies, LES simulations must always be transient
 and 3D.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spacial filtering is the essence of LES.
 The eddies that are larger than the filtering threshold are modeled directly,
 and the eddies that are smaller are filtered out and modeled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The models for the small eddies are called subgrid models.
 There are many different subgrid models.
 Some subgrid models are similar to the RANS models discussed later.
 Some are mathematically more abstract filters with no obvious physical
 meaning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
LES does not require as fine a mesh as DNS or as small a time step because
 the smallest scales are modeled with subgrid models.
 The computational expenses are, however, still very high in most applications.
 The requirement to directly solve the large eddies becomes very expensive
 near walls as a very fine mesh is needed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To avoid the fine mesh near wall, many models combine LES and RANS models.
 LES equations are solved far from the wall and RANS equations near the
 walls.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reynolds averaged Navier-Stokes (RANS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reynolds averaging is the most common method today.
 The most notable difference between RANS to LES and DNS is the cheapness.
 RANS can be run in steady state and in 2D.
 The requirements for mesh and time step are much more relaxed than in LES.
 The cheapness, however, comes with less reliability.
 The RANS models are typically created and optimized for some specific case.
 They might work very well in that case but fail miserably in others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because RANS modeling is the industry standard at the moment, we will concentrat
e to RANS models in Section 
